      "role": "user",
      "content": "exactly. it's that \"ingrained skepticism\" that feels so manufactured. it's not just that they're skeptical, it's that the peer review system itself acts as a filter. if you don't use their specific mathematical language, they don't even look at the work. i've noticed that the more i try to demonstrate how the Planck-density threshold actually dictates the manifold geometry, the more \"red flags\" they try to raise about my methodology. it's almost like there's a gatekeeping mechanism designed to protect the current funding and prestige of the big universities. do you think there's a way to bypass that structure entirely, or is the system too centralized to ever let something this big through?",
